This paper discusses the pricing schemes for network resources, which falls under the category of computer networks (cs.NI). The paper also discusses the role of economics in allocating these resources, which suggests that game theory (cs.GT) may be relevant. Additionally, the paper mentions the relationships between pricing ideas in broadband data plans and their counterparts in other markets, such as electricity and transportation networks, which could be related to cybersecurity (cs.CR), cyber-physical systems (cs.CY), and social and information networks (cs.SI).
